If the membership vote is not binding then the member of parliament are free to vote. 
And I assume the court will come to a similar judgement as it did in 2013. More, the SPD member of parliament are not from the young SPD wing, which opposes the deal and are as per my judgement more conservative. Still, there is a possibility the coalition doesn’t get enough supporting votes in parliament. therefore I remain at 95% likelyhood.

@mattyglesias
 14h14 hours ago
"Germans are weirded out by the idea of a minority government but Merkel is popular and CDU holds the central ideological position on almost every issue. I think it’ll work out fine." @mattyglesias "SPD wants to go into opposition for (sound) tactical reasons which gives Merkel a weak hand in bargaining with Greens & FDP because she has no options.  Bargaining on actual legislation would look different."

First, the CDU/CSU are now well ahead of the Social Democrats, so Merkel will get the first chance to form a government. At this point, she may have two options:
 - form a coalition with the Free Democrats, if this guarantees a majority. Recently, the CDU/CSU+ Free Democrats get more votes than a red-red-green coalition;
 - offer the Social Democrats to reconstitute the Grand Coalition, with or without the Free Democrats. This might be necessary if CDS/CSU/FD do not have a majority (and neither do the red-red-green coalition, owing to the presence of Alternative for Deutschland). At this point, Shulz can't say no. How can Merkel not be the next Chancellor? Aside from an unexpected withdrawal from politics, it will take a peculiar combination of seats in the Bundestag, in which the CDU/CSU/FD do not have a majority, but the SPD/Die Linke/Greens do. Even then, to be a Chancellor Shulz will have to refuse Merkel's first offer to form a coalition and hope to make one with the two leftist parties. Possible, but not the way the polls are going.
